	<clause id="examples_of_file_certificate_and_signature_formats" obligation="normative"><title>Examples of File, Certificate and Signature Formats</title><p id="_1616aa66-b6f3-4953-9aa0-1662aa969cc5">The following section includes a set of examples of all the various files associated with this aspect of the S-63 Data Protection Scheme. A detailed explanation of how these files are created is outlined later in this document.</p>
	<clause id="pqg_format" obligation="normative"><title>PQG Format</title><p id="_a4ce286b-446a-449f-ad89-26f4878e6db9">The PQG parameters are produced from a random string and are used in the creation of the X and Y private/public key pairs. After these have been made, the PQG parameters will be contained within the X and Y private/public key pairs.</p>
	<p id="_4887016b-0d8a-40cb-8312-520a66c3ff79">P, Q and G are numerical parameters used in the Digital Signature Algorithm as input to the key creation process. Each data server can use a different set of P, Q and G or use an existing set to generate random key pairs. The Digital Signature Standard <eref type="inline" bibitemid="dss" citeas="NIST FIPS 186"/> describes their derivation and use.</p>
	<example id="_e74cbaaf-ccc9-4f1f-b739-417f5c43ca7a" unnumbered="true">
	<name>Example of PQG Format</name>
